Germany: A Budgetary Favourite That Costs a Lot
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing vehement attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was Germany that insisted on this principle being incorporated into the Maastricht Treaty criteria, which set the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone entailed a change in political regime.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France, in the ratification referendum on the Maastricht Treaty in 1992, was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, it has become a common practice, if one may say so, to put pressure on the central bank.
For several months now, even the Minister of Finance, Wolgang Schaüble, regularly comments on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions attack the very heart of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
Although he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (that "price norm" in the old jargon of the Bundesbank), he nevertheless provides his advice on the tools that the ECB should use and how it should handle them to achieve such a goal.
We know of precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then German Finance Minister, went with his good advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was to create, in the end, a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typically Dutch laconism, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, it was absolutely unusual). "Yet – he added – it would be quite abnormal to take into account [his] suggestions."

The respect for the independence of monetary policy has been a central element of German Stability culture for a long time.
The founding act of the reputation of strict independence acquired by the Bundesbank was its refusal to give in to the Chancellor Konrad Adenauer's exhortations, who wanted it to contain the increase in interest rates, in 1956.
At this time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the verge of creating the Fifth Republic, with a Bank of France that reported to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following the various crises that shook the UEM, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace budgetary policy.
Has the old dogma become outdated?
Europe remains very vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the UEM has already lost ten years and, what is even more alarming, we are close to the critical situation.
The United States, however, are doing better.
Despite a difficult political blockade to manage, they have managed to tackle the macroeconomic problem (global demand weakness) they were facing by launching expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States have also better managed their banking problems, which, at the outset, were much more serious than in Europe.
(There is, of course, a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in both areas.
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are, and the better they are able to fulfill their function: to finance the economy.)
However, the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a Finance Minister than by the lack of support from the population.
In fact, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank was based less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, notably in Germany, calling for it to be subject to greater pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy lies in the unbearable burden weighing on its shoulders.
The less budget policy is solicited to stabilize production, the more central banks are de facto forced to take charge of this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course, and allow the economy to stagnate, or worse).
The political outcome of this chain of events is a very clear regression towards nationalism, both on the right and the left, in all UEM countries, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the pursued policies.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany leads the dance, with its obsession with the schwarze Null, budgetary balance, against the wind and the tide.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably, not only from an arithmetic point of view, but also from a moral point of view, even if this defies sound economic sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the 19th century, the main German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, forged a "golden rule" according to which current expenses must be financed, on average, by current revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, are justified by their usefulness.
This means that investments intended to improve productivity – equipment expenditures – can be financed with debt, the service of which is ensured by growth in income and the tax base associated with it.
This classic line of conduct was institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenses and investment expenses, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and in Austria).
It's crucial, because in Germany, approximately 50% of public sector investment expenses are managed at this level (a declining proportion, since the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenses are consistent with supporting the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (mittelstand).
However, in comparison to the beginning of the 1990s and at constant prices, investment expenses have decreased by approximately 15%.
More than a decade ago, they have been insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how one prepares the future, it is how one digs the hole for productivity and prosperity.
In short, the schwarze Null goes against the intended purpose.
Outdated infrastructures (certainly not as much as in the US) have become a real problem for Germany.
In addition, the German leaders' budgetary frugality spills over German borders and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which does not have an exchange rate to accommodate national particularities.
Naturally, the European Monetary Union is imperfect.
But making scapegoat of the only institution willing to "do what's necessary" to get the euro zone back on track is a very bad idea.
Had the States make use, where available, of the budgetary space at their disposal to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, has some room for maneuver in this regard.
